description: Anticipatory Action to mitigate the expected effects of below-average rainfall on food security and livelihoods in north-eastern Kenya
destOrganization: Food & Agriculture Organization of the United Nations

description: This project is designed to provide emergency relief assistance to 11,655 men, women, elderly people and disabled people to sustain their lives through provision of emergency food assistance, WASH and Protection. The project will intervene in 03 woredas which are highly affected by armed conflict.

The objective of the proposed intervention is to ensure that the basic needs of the most vulnerable displaced persons, returnees and host families in the Central African. Republic are met by implementing a response to immediate needs. Oxfam will adopt a multi-sectoral approach combining EFSL, WASH and Protection, with the aim of facilitating holistic assistance tailored to the needs of the vulnerable people targeted.
destPlan: Central African Republic Humanitarian Response Plan 2021

description: In response to the current water and food shortages caused by the ‘triple threat’ of drought, locust and COVID-19 in Eastern Somaliland, Oxfam and local partner Taakulo will support 43,800 rural IDPs and host communities (pastoralists) with integrated WASH and Food Security interventions in the Sool, Sanaag and Togdheer regions

The IDPs in Marib are extremely vulnerable and suffer the effects of multiple consecutive displacements due to conflict. Oxfam and local partner organisation BCHR will implement an integrated response in 4 IDP camps in Marib in the sectors Emergency Food Security; Water and Sanitation and Protection targeting approximately 5 000 households.
destGlobalClusters: Food Security,Protection,Protection - Child Protection,Protection - Gender-Based Violence,Protection - Mine Action,Water Sanitation Hygiene

description: Distribution of 415 emergency shelter kits and the provision of technical support for their installation, addressing essential needs of around 2,905 individuals. Improving the living conditions and enhance protection and dignity of the most vulnerable among the recently displaced communities. In particular, the intervention will provide protection from elements, improving health and safety, will reduce GBV related risks and, reducing the burden on host communities, and will contribute to foster social cohesion. Targeting IDPs currently hosted in schools would also support the access to education.

Multisectoral emergency assistance, (NFIs and food assistance) to 1,000 newly displaced households (approximately 6,000 people, estimating 6 persons per household), including 55% of women and girls directly affected by the conflict. Dignity kits and water treatment inputs, distributed-, water supplied to women and girls in reproductive age (contributions of UNFPA and UNICEF). Handwashing kit provided as a measure to prevent Covid-19.

The proposed response aims at providing 4,500 vulnerable individuals (750 households including IDPs and Host Community) directly affected by the post-electoral crisis in CAR, with an emergency assistance of essential household items (NFI), food, access to water, sanitation and hygiene, as well as protection
destPlan: Central African Republic Humanitarian Response Plan 2021

description: The worsening humanitarian context in Tigray Region resulting from the conflict between the Federal Government and Tigray Regional Administration needs an urgent, coordinated, and integrated response to save lives, contain the humanitarian crisis, and ensure people are protected. The response will focus on providing life-saving assistance, through the distribution of food commodity vouchers/cash for displacement affected population in Tigray region. The response will pay specific attention to vulnerable groups like children, women, and people with disabilities. The project aims to reach 1700 HHs (8500 individuals) with food voucher assistance.
destEmergency: Ethiopia Tigray Complex Emergency

description: Emergency assistance and shelter as part of a coordinated humanitarian response to address the devastation of a catastrophic fire which raged through camps 8E, 8W, 9, 10 and 11 on March 22nd – leaving over 45,000 people displaced and the complete destruction of 10,000 shelters. The emergency response approach of this project is split into two main activities: 1. Provision of immediate material assistance (water, dry food, non-food items) to the newly displaced to address their urgent basic needs; 2. Provision of emergency shelter materials and support to replace/rehabilitate destroyed or damaged homes.
destPlan: Bangladesh: Rohingya Refugee Crisis Joint Response Plan 2021

description: Provision of integrated package of multi-purpose cash assistance, hygiene items, NFIs and emergency education with psycho-social support to newly displaced families as a result of armed conflict in South East Myanmar.

In response to the camp displacement of 150,000 IDPs in West Darfur into 84 informal settlements in Geneina City NRC will seek to engage in Camp Management (CM) and Information Services to address the current humanitarian gaps in coordination and response. This CM response will reduce duplications, highlight priority needs and coordinate activities. The CM will help ensure that all people are better able to access life-saving services and improve the accountability of the overall response to affected people themselves. The CM team will coordinate with other agencies, UN organisations and local government. Additionally, the CM will ensure that communities have reliable two-feedback for their concerns, have gender representation in their community groups and receive reliable information on the ongoing situation.

This project will target the most vulnerable communities in rural villages of Afmadow districts that are not currently supported by other humanitarian actors with water supply and hygiene kits, through vouchers. A total of 1,398 HH (8,388 individuals) will be reached with an emergency water supply of 10 litres per person per day for 45 days. The most vulnerable 500 households from the same communities will receive hygiene kits through voucher as a one-time intervention, in addition to hygiene promotion awareness.For purposes of completeness of response and given that no rains have fallen to date, this action will be sequenced and aligned to other actions in particular those to be supported by FCDO, ECHO, UNHCR and the EU to ensure that the target population does not fall back into deep vulnerability and destituation after this Sida funded response. Coordinated consultation with multiple donors and INGOs are ongoing.
